Placemark.name: Gropius, Walter
Placemark.description:
Berlin, Gropiusstadt
1962-1975

Planned as an extension of Taut's
Hufeisensiedlung, it was originally designed
to provide 14.500 housing unities in 5 storey
buildings. With the construction of the Wall
in 1961, plans were modified (against Gropius'
will) in order to increase densities, creating
18.500 unities for more than 50.000 people
in 264 ha.

Famous through the book and film

Placemark.name: Krebs, Thomas
Placemark.description:
Augsburg, Fuggerei social housing
séc XVI

photo: High Contrast CC
The Fuggerei is the world's oldest social housing complex still in work. It was first built between 1514 and 1523 under the supervision of the architect Thomas Krebs, and in 1582 Hans Holl added the church to the settlement. Expanded further in 1880 and 1938, the Fuggerei today comprises 67 houses with 147 apartments, a well and an administrative building.
